<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
A very distinctive species because of its liana habit, persistent bracteoles appressed to the calyx, large tomentellous sepals and pink flowers. The whole plant is subtomentose with whitish hairs. The very long sepals (14-22 mm in length) serve to distinguish it from other somewhat similar species, such as 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">A.L. Brochado</emphasis>
154 (IBGE, OXF) from P.N. Das Emas, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Goiás">Goias</normalizedToken>
may constitute the first modern collection from Brazil. However, although the inflorescence is similar, the leaves lack the characteristic reticulate venation on the underside.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
